            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "After the first measure, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " i.e. according to the measure of the first and ancient cubit. By which it is evident that there were cubits of different sorts and sizes; which also appears from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Ezekiel 40:5 43:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezekiel 40:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " 43:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But how big those cubits were, and how much larger than the common cubits, and whether this was the cubit used by Moses in the building of the tabernacle, which seems most probable, or some other and yet larger cubit, is not agreed among learned men, and cannot now be exactly known, nor is it of any great moment for us to know. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
